- The carboxylic acid group significantly influences melting point due to its ability to form strong hydrogen bonds with other molecules, leading to a substantial increase in melting point. The effect of this group can be estimated at an increase of +70 degrees Celsius as it can form dimers through intermolecular hydrogen bonding, which would greatly stabilize the crystal structure.

- The hydroxyl group also forms hydrogen bonds, but its effect is less than the carboxylic acid due to only one hydrogen bonding site compared to the dimerization capability of the acid group. The hydroxyl group can be estimated to increase the melting point by roughly +30 degrees Celsius.

Summing up the changes from the functional groups for the benzene base value gives us a predicted increase of +120 degrees Celsius.
